Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

Renewable energy sources play an increasingly important role in the global energy mix, as the effort to reduce the environmental impact of energy production increases.

Out of all the renewable energy alternatives, wind energy is one of the most developed technologies worldwide. The U.S Department of Energy has put together a guide to achieving operational efficiency using predictive maintenance practices.

Predictive maintenance uses sensor information and analysis methods to measure and predict degradation and future component capability. The idea behind predictive maintenance is that failure patterns are predictable and if component failure can be predicted accurately and the component is replaced before it fails, the costs of operation and maintenance will be much lower.

The sensors fitted across different machines involved in the process of energy generation collect data related to various environmental factors (temperature, humidity, wind speed, etc.) and additional features related to various parts of the wind turbine (gearbox, tower, blades, break, etc.).

Objective¶

ReneWind is a company working on improving the machinery/processes involved in the production of wind energy using machine learning and has collected data of generator failure of wind turbines using sensors. They have shared a ciphered version of the data, as the data collected through sensors is confidential (the type of data collected varies with companies). Data has 40 predictors, 20000 observations in the training set and 5000 in the test set.

The objective is to build various classification models, tune them, and find the best one that will help identify failures so that the generators could be repaired before failing/breaking to reduce the overall maintenance cost. The nature of predictions made by the classification model will translate as follows:

  • True positives (TP) are failures correctly predicted by the model. These will result in repairing costs.
  • False negatives (FN) are real failures where there is no detection by the model. These will result in replacement costs.
  • False positives (FP) are detections where there is no failure. These will result in inspection costs.

It is given that the cost of repairing a generator is much less than the cost of replacing it, and the cost of inspection is less than the cost of repair.

1 in the target variables should be considered as failure and 0 represents No failure.

Data Description¶

  • The data provided is a transformed version of original data which was collected using sensors.
  • Train.csv - To be used for training and tuning of models.
  • Test.csv - To be used only for testing the performance of the final best model.
  • Both the datasets consist of 40 predictor variables and 1 target variable

Statistical Summary¶

  • Since there are too many continuous numerical variables, we limit their statistical summary only to the training data. Nonetheless, both datasets are supposed to have come from the same populations (distributions), therefore study of one should give insights into the other as well.
  • We will convert the target variable into a categorical variable, with its classes being labeled as 'No Failure' and 'Failure' only for statistical summary and univariate analysis parts.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

In [16]:
# Auxiliary function for annotating the bars in a countplot
def countplot_labeling(cntplt, data, perc = True, decimal = 1):
  ''' This function gets a countplot and the dataset that has generated
  the plot to produce the values corresponding to each bar (category).
  If perc = True, percentages will be shown.'''

  from math import isnan

  total = data.shape[0]  # total number of values in the dataset
  for p in cntplt.patches:
        height_val = float(p.get_height())
        if(isnan(height_val)):
          height_val = 0
        if(abs(height_val - round(height_val)) < 1e-6):
          height_val = int(height_val)  
        if perc == True:
          # percentage of each category
          label = "{:.1f}%".format(100*height_val/total)
        else:
          label = "{}".format(round(height_val,decimal))  # count of each category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        if(height_val == 0):
          label = '0'

        # annotate the bar
        cntplt.annotate(label, (x, y), ha = "center", va = "center", size = 12, xytext = (0, 5), textcoords = "offset points")

# Doing a loop over all continuous numerical columns to plot their distributions
for col in df.select_dtypes(include = np.number).columns.tolist():
    # Calculating the equivalent normal distribution (mu and sigma come from training)
    var_scale = max(abs(df[col].min()), df[col].max())
    norm_dist_x = np.linspace(-var_scale, var_scale, 200)
    norm_dist_y = stats.norm.pdf(norm_dist_x, loc = df[col].mean(), scale = df[col].std(ddof = 1))
    plt.figure(figsize = (16, 4));
    # KDE plots
    plt.subplot(121);
    sns.kdeplot(data = df, x = col, color = 'blue');
    sns.kdeplot(data = df_test, x = col, color = 'red');
    plt.axvline(df[col].mean(), linestyle = ':', color = 'blue');
    plt.plot(norm_dist_x, norm_dist_y, linestyle = '--', color = 'blue');
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Test', 'Normal']);
    # Boxplots
    plt.subplot(122);
    sns.boxplot(data = df, x = col, showmeans = True, meanprops = 
                {'marker': 'x', 'markerfacecolor': 'red', 'markeredgecolor': 'red', 'markersize': '7'});
    plt.tight_layout(w_pad = 5);

Observations:¶

  • The dashed blue lines show the equivalent normal distributions whose mean and standard deviation are identical to those of the plotted variable from the training data. The vertical dotted lines indicate the mean value of the plotted feature from the training data.
  • For the sake of comparison, the KDE plots for both training (solid blue) and testing data (solid red) have been shown. As can be seen, for all variables, the KDE plots of the training and testing datasets look very similar, indicating that both datasets have been drawn from the same populations (distributions).
  • Most variables resemble a normal distribution. For some like V6 and V38 the similarity is manifest, and for some such as V18 and V34 the match isn't strong.
  • This behavior shouldn't be surprising, as most natural phenomena and engineering processes, including those emerging in wind energy production, follow normal distributions.
  • For all variables, mean and median are fairly close to each other. Of course, when a distribution is closer to normal, the difference between the two is even smaller.
  • There are outliers appearing on both sides of the boxplot for all features, but they all look fairly continuous and part of the actual data and given distributions. Thus, none of them raises a red flag or requires outlier treatment.

Data Imputation¶

  • Missing value treatment for V1 and V2 will be carried out using K-Nearest Neighbors algorithm. The datasets mostly consist of continuous numerical variables, making an interpolation-based imputation scheme that fills in the missing records in the parameter space using the (weighted) average of the neighbors of a data point with missing values a rational choice. This will help better preserve the distributions of the features with missing values, and avoid concentrating values around the meaures of central tendency.
  • We also would like to highlight that using a KNN Imputer, instead of a Simple Imputer (with median as imputation strategy) led to the development of slightly more accurate and robust models, but for the sake of brevity, the calculations concerning the latter aren't shown.

ML-based Modeling¶

  • Here, we choose Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, Bagging Classifier, Random Forest, AdaBoost Classifier, Gradient Boosting Classifier and XGBoost Classifier as our classification models.

  • Among all costs defined in the problem statement, replacement cost seems the most severe. Therefore, mitigating this type of damage should be our first priority, which is only accomplished by reducing the number of FNs. Towards this end, we select maximizing recall score as our primary objective, which attempts to identify as many potential failures.

In [24]:
# Auxiliary function for reporting the evaluation metrics of models
def model_eval(model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, valid = True):
    '''This function calculates all relevant evaluation metrics for the classification
    model passed to it on training and validation/test sets and returns it as a dataframe.'''

    # Reconstructing the training set
    y_recon = model.predict(X_train)
    # Forecasting the validation/test set
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    # Defining the dataframe of performance metrics
    if valid:
        metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(index = ['Train', 'Validation'], columns = 
                                  ['Accuracy', 'Recall', 'Precision', 'F1', 'Specificity'])
    else:  
        metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(index = ['Train', 'Test'], columns = 
                                  ['Accuracy', 'Recall', 'Precision', 'F1', 'Specificity'])

    # Filling in the evaluation metrics
    metrics_df.iloc[0, :] = [accuracy_score(y_train, y_recon), recall_score(y_train, y_recon),
                             precision_score(y_train, y_recon), f1_score(y_train, y_recon),
                             recall_score(y_train, y_recon, pos_label = 0)]
    metrics_df.iloc[1, :] = [accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred), recall_score(y_test, y_pred),
                             precision_score(y_test, y_pred), f1_score(y_test, y_pred),
                             recall_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label = 0)]
    return metrics_df
In [25]:
# Auxiliary function for plotting the confusion matrix of classification models
def plot_cm(y_truth, y_pred):
    '''This function receives the actual data (y_truth) and the predictions of a
    classification model (y_pred), and returns the confusion matrix of the two in
    the form of a heatmap.'''

    # Calculating the confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_truth, y_pred)
    # Trurning the confusion matrix into a dataframe
    cm_df = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = ['Truth -- No Failure', 'Truth -- Failure'], 
                         columns = ['Prediction -- No Failure', 'Prediction -- Failure'])

    # Generating the labels of the heatmap
    labels = []
    for i in range(len(cm.flatten())):
        labels.append(str(cm.flatten()[i]) + '\n(' + str(round(cm.flatten()[i]/cm.flatten().sum()*100, 2)) + '%)')
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2, 2)

    # Potting the heatmap of the confusion matrix
    sns.heatmap(cm_df, fmt = '', annot = labels, cbar = False, cmap = 'seismic',
                vmin = -1.05*len(y_truth), vmax = 1.05*len(y_truth))
    plt.xlabel('Prediction');
    plt.ylabel('Truth');

Observations:¶

  • With the exception of Logistic Regression Classifier, which inherently isn't prone to overfitting, and to some degree AdaBoost Classifier, all other models notably suffer from overfitting.
  • The problem of overfitting is more manifest for the decision tree and bagging models compared to the boosting models. This is most likely attributed to the fact that boosting methods use simplified models (weak learners) as their base estimators by default.
  • Accuracy scores on the validation set is quite high for all models, but as discussed before, accuracy isn't a good measure for identifying the best model, due to the significant imbalance between classes. An accuracy of ~ 95% can be achieved just by labeling all target values as 'No Failure'.
  • The Bagging Classifier has the highest validation recall score, but this model isn't very reliable and robust, due to its severe overfitting issue.
  • Since the cost of missing any failure is drastic, recall scores around 70% (or even 81% of the XGBoost Classifier) aren't that impressive. Therefore, we seek to further improve the current performance of the models by resapmling, and erasing the imbalance in the data.

Oversampling¶

Here, we apply the same untuned models as above to upsampled data.

Observations:¶

  • Oversampling has significantly improved the recall score on the training and more importantly the validation set, and now the validation recall score hovers around 0.85 (except for the Decision Tree classifier whose recall is 0.77), as the bias toward the majority class has been eliminated.
  • All models still suffer from overfitting. Even the Logistic Regression and AdaBoost Classifiers that weren't troubled by this problem very seriously before, now see significant drop in their precision and F1 scores moving from training to validation set.
  • It is noteworthy how well the XGBoost Classifier performs on both sets. While the gap between recall score on training and validation has been reduced by oversampling, the validation precision score has also remained quite high.

Observations:¶

  • The recall scores on validation sets have slightly improved compared to the oversamped models, but this has come at the price of significanly reducing the precision scores.
  • The major decline in precision emerges, since, in the case of undersampled models, the training set is too small with respect to its original size, as the vast majority of 'No Failure' class have been thrown out, therefore the model can't learn this class properly and, as a result, can't distinguish between the two classes accurately, thus producing many FPs on an unseen dataset (like validation set).
  • All models still suffer from overfitting. Even if their recall scores don't drop much from the training to validation set, their precision scores certainly do.

Observations:¶

  • The Decision Tree and Random Forest Classifiers return perfect score for all performance metrics on the training set, regardless of using the original or resampled data. This is because, we haven't set any constraint on the complexity of these models yet, so their trees can grow unboundedly to label every single data point correctly.
  • The XGBoost Classifier also yields 100% for all evaluation metrics on the training set. Note that the base estimator of this method is more complex than those of the the other boosing methods. For instance, by default, the max_depth of an XGBoost Classifier is 6, whereas those of the AdaBoost and Gradient Boosting Classifiers are 1 and 3, respectively.
  • The Logistic Regression model, which is less susceptible to overfitting, and the boosting methods, that use less complex base estimators, unsurprisingly fall at the bottom of the list.

Observations:¶

  • However 4 out of the top 5 best-performing models (sorted based on their validation recall scores) have been developed on the undersampled data, the improvement on recall for the undersampled models has come at the cost of substantially reducing precision. For instance, the recall score of the undersampled XGBoost Classifier is only ~ 0.04 higher than its oversampled counterpart, while the difference in their precision scores is ~ 0.35!
  • Not surprisingly, all baseline models are stacked on the bottom of the recall-based validation performance list.
  • It should be noted that, however the replacement cost is much higher than the inspection cost, the cost of too many unnecessary inspections (caused by producing too many FPs) can also add up.

Cross-Validation

In [120]:
# No. of cross-validation folds 
n_folds = 10
# List of all estimators
models_list = [lrc0, dtr0, bgc0, rfc0, abc0, gbc0, xgbc0]
# Making a dataframe for the cross-validated recall scores of all resampled models 
cv_results_df = pd.DataFrame(np.zeros([n_folds, len(models_list)*2]), 
                             columns = ['LRC (Over)', 'LRC (Under)', 'DTR (Over)', 'DTR (Under)',
                                        'BGC (Over)', 'BGC (Under)', 'RFC (Over)', 'RFC (Under)', 
                                        'ABC (Over)', 'ABC (Under)', 'GBC (Over)', 'GBC (Under)',
                                        'XGBC (Over)', 'XGBC (Under)'])
# Setting the randomized data splitting strategy
kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits = n_folds, shuffle = True, random_state = 1)
for i, model in enumerate(models_list):
    cv_results_df.iloc[:, 2*i] = cross_val_score(model, X_train_over, y_train_over,
                                                 scoring = 'recall', cv = kfold, n_jobs = -1)
    cv_results_df.iloc[:, 2*i+1] = cross_val_score(model, X_train_under, y_train_under,
                                                   scoring = 'recall', cv = kfold, n_jobs = -1)
# Plotting the boxplot distribution of cross-validated recall scores of all resampled models  
plt.figure(figsize = (18, 5))
sns.boxplot(data = cv_results_df.iloc[0:4, :], showmeans = True, dodge = True, meanprops = 
            {'marker': 'x', 'markerfacecolor': 'red', 'markeredgecolor': 'red', 'markersize': '7'});
plt.xlabel('Model');
plt.ylabel('Recall Score'); 
plt.xticks(rotation = 45);
plt.yticks(ticks = np.arange(0.8, 1.01, 0.05)); 
plt.ylim(0.8, 1);

Observations:¶

  • As can be noted, the undersampled models have typically wider confidence intervals, since they are trained on smaller datasets, increasing the uncertainty of their results.
  • The average and median cross-validated recall scores of the oversampled models are somewhat higher than those of their undersampled counterparts.
  • The recall scores of the Decision Tree, Bagging, Random Forest and XGBoost Classifiers on the oversampled data stand out from the other models. Note that these models haven't been tuned yet, i.e. their base estimators might get very complex, making them specifically tailored for the dataset on which they've been trained. The first three can grow unboundedly if no limit is set, and the default depth of the XGBoost Classifier is 6, which is much higher than that of the other boosting methods. Furthermore, they have benefitted from a synthetically large and balanced training set, with different target class frequencies compared to the validation set. Consequently, they can't replicate these high cross-validated scores on the validation set, and validation scores may not even fall in their confidence intervals.
  • The results for the baseline models weren't depicted, as it was already established that these models are inferior to the resampled models.
  • Note that the baseline and resampled models have the same hyperparameters (and are technically identical). This is why using them in the model list, instead of let's say replacing bgc0 by bgc_over or bgc_under, doesn't make any difference in the above analysis.

HyperparameterTuning¶

  • As seen above, from the recall score perspective, the best-performing models on the validation are the undersampled models. On the other hand, the oversampled models have narrower confidence intervals and higher cross-validated scores than their undersampled counterparts, and don't sacrifice precision much for the sake of maximizing recall. Therefore, we select the seven models with the highest validation recall scores for model tuning. This set of models hass a nearly balanced share of both oversampled and undersampled classifiers: three of the former and four of the latter.
  • Number of cross-validation folds for all models is set at 5, which is half of what we used for finding the confidence intervals. Note that accurate calculation of mean and standard deviation of cross-validated scores typically requires a larger number of data folds.
  • Number of random draws (n_iter) in the randomized search algorithm varies between 50 and 100, depending on the variety of hyperparameters a classification method provides.
  • For this section, we've defined our own recall scorer, yielding the correct recall score all the time, except when the recall is one, in which case, it returns zero. This is to prevent development of models that maximize recall by labeling everything class 1 ('Failure'). Additionally, using this scorer helps mitigate the overfitting problem. Note that this function will be used only inside the model tuning search algorithm, and not for calculating the actual recall score, when a model is built/tuned.
In [121]:
# In-house recall score
def my_recall(y_truth, y_pred):
    '''This function return the correct recall score except when recall = 1. 
    In that case, it returns 0.'''
    recall = recall_score(y_truth, y_pred)
    if recall == 1:
        recall = 0
    return recall

Cross-Validated Scores

In [138]:
# No. of cross-validation folds 
n_folds = 10
# List of all estimators
models_list = [bgc_tuned_us, rfc_tuned_us, abc_tuned_os, gbc_tuned_os,  
               gbc_tuned_us, xgbc_tuned_us, xgbc_tuned_os]
# Making a dataframe for the cross-validated recall scores of all resampled models 
cv_results_df = pd.DataFrame(np.zeros([n_folds, 7]), 
                             columns = ['BGC (Under)', 'RFC (Under)', 'ABC (Over)', 'GBC (Over)', 
                                        'GBC (Under)', 'XGBC (Over)', 'XGBC (Under)'])
# Setting the randomized data splitting strategy
kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits = n_folds, shuffle = True, random_state = 1)
for i, model in enumerate(models_list):
    if('Over' in cv_results_df.columns.tolist()[i]):
        X_cv = X_train_over
        y_cv = y_train_over
    else:
        X_cv = X_train_under
        y_cv = y_train_under
    cv_results_df.iloc[:, i] = cross_val_score(model, X_cv, y_cv, scoring = 'recall', cv = kfold)

# Plotting the boxplot distribution of cross-validated recall scores of all resampled models  
plt.figure(figsize = (12.5, 5))
sns.boxplot(data = cv_results_df, showmeans = True, dodge = True, meanprops = 
            {'marker': 'x', 'markerfacecolor': 'red', 'markeredgecolor': 'red', 'markersize': '7'});
plt.xlabel('Model');
plt.ylabel('Recall Score'); 
plt.ylim(0.85, 1);

Observations:¶

  • Either caused by using a randomized search, which doesn't sweep the entire hyperparameter space, or the nature of the data, model tuning didn't fully resolve the overfitting problem for all models. For instance, the tuned AdaBoost Classifier reveals perfect training scores, and a notable drop in the performance metrics on the validation set.
  • Similar to what observed for untuned classifiers, the oversampled models have higher mean and median cross-validated scores and narrower confidence intervals. But since these models are still (at least somewhat) overfit, the validation score may not even fall inside the uncertainty region.
  • The undersampled XGBoost Classifier has the highest validation recall score and a fairly decent precision (more than 50%) for a model aimed at maximizing recall. Furthermore, the validation score falls within its region of uncertainty, indicating that the evaluation metrics on any unseen data (like test set) shouldn't be too distant from the validation and cross-validated scores.

Observations:¶

  • Note that XGBoost classification is an ensemble technique, being built by hundreds of sequential weak learners, each with a different set of predictors. It thus shouldn't be surprising to see that the importance of predictors has been mixed and distributed over a wide range of features.
  • As can be noted, only predictors whose relative importance exceeds 0.01 have been shown.

# Finding the region of uncertainty for the recall score of the final model

# Setting the strategy for splitting the data into 10 random folds
kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits = 10, shuffle = True, random_state = 1)

# Calculating the cross-validated scores
cv_results = cross_val_score(clf_pipe, X_train_pipe_resampled, y_train_pipe_resampled,
                             scoring = 'recall', cv = kfold, n_jobs = -1)
cv_mean = cv_results.mean()
cv_std  = cv_results.std()

# Reporting the model's average recall score and confidence interval
print('The average recall score of the productionized model is {} and,'.format(round(cv_mean, 3)), 
      'with 95% certainty, its recall score resides between {} and {}.'.format(
          round(cv_mean-2*cv_std, 3), round(cv_mean+2*cv_std, 3))) 

The average recall score of the productionized model is 0.909 and, with 95% certainty, its recall score resides between 0.852 and 0.966.

Observations:¶

The test precision score has increased slightly after deploying the model in production, perhaps since the model has been trained on a larger training set (the whole training data), but, overall, the productionized model reveals a very similar performance as before (e.g., identical test recall score).

Business Insights and Conclusions¶

Here, we do not aim to present a lengthy summary of all findings. Instead, we briefly recapitulate major observations, and draw actionable recommendations from them.

Observations and business recommendations:

  • Both training and testing datasets exhibited a drastic imbalance between the classes of the target variable (almost a 95/5 ratio for no failure to failure), signaling that resampling is crucial to construct a robust and reliable classification model.
  • We demonstrated that the training and testing data come from the same populations, enabling the application of the ML-based models developed on the training data to the test data with no major loss of accuracy.
  • Most variables were shown to come from nearly normal distributions.
  • The final model, chosen based on its capability to maximize recall, was an undersampled and tuned XGBoost classifier with the recall score around 90% on the validation set, and almost the same (~ 87%) on the test set. It also had a decent precision score (> 50%) for a model optimized on recall.
  • The undersampled Gradient Boosting classifier also showed a very similar performance to that of the final model, but since the mean and median of its cross-validated recall scores were slightly lower (and had a faintly smaller validation recall score), we selected the XGBoost Classifier as the final model.
  • The oversampled models showed to typically have narrower confidence intervals (due to much their larger training set), but proved to be usually overfit, as their validation recall scores often didn't fall even in the confidence interval.
  • Before tuning, the bagging methods revealed to be far more prone to overfitting than boosting methods or logistic regression.
  • None of the variables really dominates the predictions of the final model. XGBoost classifier consists of hundreds of sequentially improved estimators and, due to the random mechanisms devised in it, each estimator may use a very diferent set of predictors, thus distributing the task of classification among a wide range of variables. Nonetheless, a few still stand out (e.g., V36, V18 and V39), and they may prove to be more significant indicators of failure than other predictors.

Recommendations for future ML-based modeling:

  • A few of the features with high correlation with the target also appeared to be effective predictors of the target class as well. This shows a preliminary EDA can be helpful to determine what to expect from the final classification model, and how to reasonably and effectively tweak its hyperparameters. For instance, the number of predictors with high correlation with the target may give us some idea about a suitable range for the maximum depth.
  • Using a KNN-based imputation scheme reveals to be really helpful when most vriables are numerical and continuous, and the number of missing records is small or moderate. This method can very well preserve the original distribution of variables, and doesn't cause concentration around the measures of central tendency and, consequently, doesn't cause significant reduction in standard deviation and variability. For this project, both simple imputer (using median as imputation strategy) and KNN imputer work fine and yield similar results, since only a very small fraction of entries were missing.
